column168: SOUTHEAST DRIVER NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE WHILE DEILVERING TO A CUSTOMER. SOUTHEAST ONROAD SUPERVISOR DROVE ME TO CUSTOMER'S BUSINESS TO RETRIEVE THE LEAKING PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION I NOTICED CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL ALONG WITH HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS ON THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE LEAKED IN THE DRIVER'S CAR AND AT THE CUSTOMERS BUSINESS. WHILE USING PROPER PPE (BOOTS, APRON, GOGGLES, PROTECTIVE LINERS AND GLOVES) I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL USING THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET. I CLEANED UP THE SPILL ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE (APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE AND CLAY ABSORBENT) TO SOLIDIFY THE SPILLED LIQUID. I FULLY CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITHOUT LEAVING ANY RESIDUE IN THE PACKAGE CAR OR THE CUSTOMERS BUSINESS. UPON RETURNING THE BUILDING I PROCESSED THE REMAINING LIQUID ALONG WITH THE CONTAMINATED SHIPPING MATERIAL THROUGHT THE DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. 3 OF THE 4 GALLONS WERE NOT CONTAMINATED AND WILL BE RETURNED BACK TOT HE SHIPPER IN AN APPROVED YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM.
column169: FROM OBSERVATION, I NOTICED ONE OF THE CAPS WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED ON ONE OF THE GALLONS OF PRODUCT. TO PREVENT RECURRENCE I WOULD SUGGEST THE SHIPPER TO PROPERLY SEAL ALL PRODUCT BEFORE SHIPPING.

column168: DESIGNATED RESPONDER KATHY LOEFFLER RESPONDED TO A REPORT OF A HAZMAT SPILL ON THE CATWALK BETWEEN DOORS 164 AND 165 ON THE RED BELT OUTBOUND AREA. WHEN SHE ARRIVED SHE DONNED AN APRON, BOOTS, GOGGLES, GLOVES, AND SILVER SHIELDS UNDER THE GLOVES. SHE SAW THAT THE PACKAGE HAD CORROSIVE HAZMAT MARKINGS (CATEGORY 8) AND PROCEEDED TO FOLLOW THE STEPS OUTLINED IN THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET. WHEN TESTED FOR PH BY KATHY, THE MATERIAL SHOWED TO BE A STRONG BASE, ABOVE THE 6-9 RANGE. SHE APPLIED NEUTRALIZER UNTIL THE MATERIAL SHOWED A PH WITHIN THE 6-9 RANGE, THEN CLEANED UP A SMALL SPILL OF IT, PLACED THE PACKAGE AND ABSORBED MATERIAL IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND TRANSPORTED IT TO THE DMP AREA. BILL HIGGINS THEN PROCESSED THE MATERIAL THROUGH DMP ACCORDING TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR A FULL DMMP FACILITY.

MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGE AND IN THE INVOICE INDICATED THE ITEM WAS VEROBLACKPLUS RGD875 INK. column168: SHPX 205090 was found to have an odor release by the Car Department in the Roseville receiving yard. I responded and found that the odor was from the top of the tank car. I had a low level reading of VOC on my air monitor at the manway. The manway was missing its gasket. I applied a temp gasket with PTFE joint sealant and re-secured the car. I had no more readings on the air monitor and no odor was present.  Around noon the Car Department reported that the tank car was making a hissing noise. I was committed to training out of the area, so I dispatched Patriot Environmental Emergency Response Contractor to investigate. They found that once the car built pressure it began to leak at the overlap of the temporary gasket. They readjusted the gasket and secured the tank car. This stopped the leak.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Upon arrival gasoline was leaking from the bottom outlet cap. This car was equipped with a top operated bottom outlet valve. Before the stuffing box cover was removed it was noticed that the seal was not the shippers seal. After further inspection the valve was two turns open. The valve was closed and the leak stopped. The bottom outlet cap was removed and the gasket was inspected the gasket exhibited deterioration through normal wear the gasket was replaced on the bottom outlet cap, the cap was secured and the car was released back to transportation.

On 5 MAR 2016, at 1200, personnel in the CSXT Tilford discovered TCIX6247, a loaded tank car of sodium hydroxide solution, leaking from the bottom of the car. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On March 10, 2016 at 11:28 hours personnel in the CSX Boyles Yard reported GATX 2947, a loaded tank car of Carbon Dioxide, venting loudly.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Air Liquide, was notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2016-03-10-00159). USES, a CSX response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative James Montalbano (713-896-2316).  After allowing the car to relieve the necessary pressure, CSX Hazardous Material Team personnel returned to the site on March 12, 2016 and installed a new rupture disc. The car will be held out of transportation until such time that the internal temperature of the car rises to a level that is safe for transportation. column168: The road tank trailer was loaded onto ocean vessel and found to be leaking. The tank was then off loaded to a well ventilated isolated area and a large pail placed under the dripping area. Shipper was notified and resources to stop the leak were requested at or around 5:30pm. Owner of the tank called at or around 9:00pm stating a loose bolt easily accessible was the culprit. Tank was re-inspected at or around 8:15am and still found to be leaking and repair was not possible after a bolt was found to be missing connecting the main rear port to the tanks rear underside. Tank owner stated that a repair technician was enroute. The repair technician arrived and stated the repair was beyond his scope. Tank owner and shipper then stated another tank and repair technician was enroute to repair the leak and transfer the product. The 2nd tank and technician failed to arrive so FD assumed control, closed the specific area of the seaport and Cliff Berry Inc. transferred product in tank into another tank successfully stopping the leak.
column169: Tank loading company should better inspect tanks intended to be loaded.

column168: DRUMS WERE BEING LOADED ONTO A VAN TRAILER BY A FORKLIFT. ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED ON THE LOWER FRONT SIDE AS THE DRUM MADE CONTACT WITH THE PROTRUDING HEAD OF A FASTENER THAT WAS CONNECTING THE BOTTOM FRONT BASEBOARD TO THE FRAME OF THE TRAILER. LIQUID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING OUT OF THE PACKAGE ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ONTO THE PAVEMENT UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER. ABSORBENT CLAY (SPEDI-DRI) WAS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WHILE THE DRUM WAS SECURED AND TRANSFERRED INTO A DIFFERENT CONTAINER. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACIDIC MATERIAL. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 2 GALLONS TOTAL OF LIQUID WERE RELEASED FROM THE DRUM OF WHICH AN ESTIMATED 1 GALLON WAS SPILLED ONTO THE PAVEMENT BELOW. ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND COLLECTED INTO A CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: THE TRAILER FASTENERS WHICH WERE LOOSE WERE REMOVED AND THE BASEBOARD WAS REINSTALLED WITH NEW FASTENERS. A TRAILER INSPECTION PROCEDURE WAS IMPLEMENTED TO CHECK FOR LOOSE FASTENERS AND OTHER POTENTIAL SHARP POINTS WHICH COULD PUNCTURE CONTAINERS IN FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

THE IRREG SORTER NEAR DOOR 180 OF THE IRREG BELT WAS SLIDING A HAZMAT PACKAGE FROM THE BELT TO THE ROLLER PLATFORM WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. HE LEFT IT ON THE PLATFORM NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. THE PACKAGE WAS FLAMMABLE SO NO CHANGES TO PPE WERE NECESSARY. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ALL LIQUID ON THE PLATFORM. I SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANT ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY WITH THE PACKAGE. AFTER CHECKING TO MAKE SURE ALL RESIDUE WAS REMOVED, I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 BOTTLES HAD CRACKED.
RESPONDED TO SPILL WEARING PROPER PPE. USE THE DECISION TREE RESPONSE SHEET TO DETERMINE PROPER METHODS AND PROCEDURES FOR CLEANING UP AND SPILL AND TRANSPORTED PACKAGE TO DMP FOR PROCESSING.

column168: On March 10, 2016 at 13:00 hours, an FRA inspector reported an exception to PROX 13618, a loaded UN 1832, Sulfuric Acid, Spent, tank car to have released product from the protective housing area.  The car was isolated and the Shipper, Chemtrade Logistics was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2016-03-10-00180.  A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro - Schererville, IN branch office, was dispatched to the scene.  Upon inspection it was determined the sulfuric acid appeared to be leaking from the liquid line cap and that the railcar was pressurized to 9 psi.  SUNPRO depressurized the railcar and removed the liquid line cap.  The project manager noted that no threading tape or leak dope was present on the liquid line.  The response team affixed threading tape onto the liquid line opening and reinstalled the cap.  SUNPRO utilized fresh water and absorbent pads to neutralize and recover the spilled sulfuric acid from the exterior of the railcar.     Cause Code: 117 at 5 points  NARRI: 5 (5 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 03/23/16 at 1521 hours it was discovered at Goulding Yard (CSXT), located in Pensacola, FL, that tank car SCMX2801, a residue Molten Phenol, to be venting vapor from liquid line and vapor line. The shipper, Ascend Performance Materials, was notified. United States Environmental Services, CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. CSX Hazmat Manager Page and USES climbed the car and found the liquid line plug and vapor line plug installed less than  turn venting product vapor into the air.  It was also discovered that the housing cover was partially open and the housing pin was not installed.  CSX Hazmat Manager Page and USES secured both plugs securing the vapor release.  Upon securing both plugs and securing the housing cover the product odor dissipated and no abnormal air monitoring readings were observed. These actions were communicated to the shipper (Ed Waldynski). The car was secured and released.    NAR Cause Code: 115  Liquid Line/ Liquid Valve closure plug less than tool tight    5(5+1+5) x (2+4) = 330 NARRI     Pensacola, FL 03/23/16  SCMX2801  Molten Phenol
column169: Ensure secondary closures/ plugs are installed and properly secured.  Ensure housing cover pin is installed and secured.

A roll off box container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. was parked at the Clean Harbors Lake Point, UT storage facility pending transportation to the Clean Harbors Aragonite, UT disposal facility. During a routine pre trip vehicle inspection the driver discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door seal of the roll off box container leaking onto the trailer fender. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material, solidified the load with absorbent, and placed the released material back into the vacuum box. The shipment continued on to the disposal destination. The amount of material released was below the reportable quantity threshold.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors' Kimball, NE facility it was determined the vacuum box was leaking due to the presence of free liquid. In order to prevent a recurrence, the initial shipper has been notified of the improper preparation and presence of free liquids in a solid waste stream, the driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, this specific container was placed out of service pending an inspection of the door seal.

column168: There was no failure by the carrier or the package in this incident. The release during the loading process occurred due to an open cleanout valve on the top of the product filter housing.     Carrier arrived and operations began the loading process at 15:33. At approximately 15:45, GP operations became aware that the formaldehyde solution was flowing from the open cleanout on the filer housing. The loading process was aborted, and the area cleaned of spilled material, which was diluted and reclaimed for further use in the production process.     Once the incident had been resolved, the loading process with the carrier was completed without further incident. Due to the spill exceeding the RQ, notifications were made to NRC, SERC and LEPC. This follow-up report was prompted due to the process equipment failure being a part of an active cargo tank loading operation. Other than the carrier delay, there was no impact to the carrier or the package with this incident.
column169: The prompt implementation of the facility spill response procedures helped minimize the extent of the release. To prevent recurrence of a similar release, the Columbus plant is planning to replace the secondary valve on the filter assembly with a spring loaded valve which requires it to be physically held open to safely release pressure prior to opening and accessing the filters for cleaning. GP anticipates that improvements should be in place by end of Q2/2016.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED FROM THE UNLOAD. THE BAG WAS TRANSPORTED OVER THE BELT TO THE SMALL SORT AREA. THE PACKAGE WAS SCANNED AND SENT BACK TO THE UNLOAD. column169: DON'T TOUCH, LEAVE THE AREA AND NOTIFY A SUPERVISOR.

The courier for WPX (JMC) brought a sealed WPX bag containing 4 boxes of misrouted meds to be sent to Anchorage. After accepting the shipment, I x-rayed the bag and saw it contained aerosol cans. After opening the boxes I discovered: seven, 11 oz cans of hairspray, ten, 10oz cans of shaving cream, eight, 7 oz shaving cream, three, 6 oz bottles of acetone polish remover and three, 2 oz bottles of polish removers. The boxes inside the bag were all marked ORMDA. I stopped the shipment and filed this report.
column169: WPX frequently sends shipments with multiple med orders in one large box or bag. They need to be aware of the contents of all shipments.

column168: I WAS WALKING TO LOOK FOR SUPPLIES WHEN THE CHARGER ON THE YELLOW BELT TOLD ME HE HAD A LEAKER. I WENT BACK AND DONNED APPROPRIATE PPE AND RESPONDED TO THE SOILED PACKAGE.
column169: THE SHIPPING LABEL WAS ON THE SIDE OF THE PACKAGE. IF THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED LABEL UP IN CONTRADICTION TO THE ORIENTATION LABELS THEN THAT'S HOW THE LIQUID LEAKED OUT. THE SPILLED LIQUID SOILED THE BOX BUT DIDN'T APPEAR TO RESULT IN ANY LIQUID BEING RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. WORKING WITH THE SHIPPER TO PUT THE SHIPPING LABEL ON TOP OF THE BOX INSTEAD OF THE SIDE WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS OCCURRENCE.

column168: DRIVER ORLANDO JOHNSON FROM PETRO EXPRESS CO WAS TRAVELING S.B ON RT 3 CRAIN HWY IN THE RIGHT LANE. column25: RPMG, Inc. (prior orgin: Chippewa Valley Ethanol Co LLC)
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 03/02/2016, FRA Hazmat Inspector Randy Boyington identified the NATX 37067 as possibly leaking as evidence from an audible "hiss" heard from ground level.  Mr. Boyington suggested the Vacuum Relief Valve was leaking.  BNSF Hazmat Responders isolated the car and found that the Vacuum Relief Valve was indeed leaking a small amount of vapor only.  There was no evidence of a liquid release of ethanol from the fitting.  BNSF contractors arrived and removed the defective Vacuum Relief Valve and replaced it with a 2 1/2" plug.  The VRV was secured under the multi-housing cover for shipper inspection and root cause analysis.  No immediate defects were noted with the VRV at the time.  The shipper (RPMG) then obtained an OTMA 3 for movement of the package for offloading and to home shop for repairs and testing.
column169: Shipper has been notified to ensure that equipment inspections and servicing of equipment procedures are reviewed and amended if necessary to prevent future occurrences.

column168: On March 25, 2016, a straight truck suffered from a cargo release. 1-55 gallon steel drum of UN1263, White Polyester Paint,3, II was damaged. Approximately 1 gallon of product was immediately released to the trailer floor due to a crease in the drum that occurred when the drum was loaded on the truck. Contractor used absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor generated 1-55 gallon drum of impacted absorbents, debris and PPE for waste.

On 3/13/2016 at 2227 hours, Jeffrey Taylor, CSX Trainmaster, reported to the CSX Public Safety Coordination Center that tank car UCLX 461090 had a single, non-constant, vapor release from the top of the car during yard operations. This was a isolated event witnessed by yard crews, and once reported the car was isolated until the morning of 3/14/2016.    On 3/14/2016 at 1321 hours, the top mounted liquid line flange was found to have 4 of 4 flange securement fasteners less than tool tight, and residue of material outside of the flange was discovered to have a detectable pH reading consistent with the contents of the car. All securement fasteners were appropriately tightened and residue removed.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: At approximately 10:18am ERT received a priority 2 call for copper waste release outside of CUB A. The release occurred during the loading of a copper filter cake rolloff (F006 Hazardous Waste). The container had been removed from the building to load for transport. When lifted to a 45 degree angle to load onto the truck, liquid from inside the rolloff leaked out through the door. Enpro personnel (the Carrier) responded immediately by blocking off the nearby sewer drain and lowering the rolloff; minimizing the volume that reached the environment.  An estimated 200-300ml reached a stormwater catch basin (which does not discharge offsite). Enpro's quick action prevented the release from exceeding the CERCLA RQ.    The emergency response team arrived at the scene to clean up the spill using absorbent pads and granular absorbent material.  The catch basin was also pumped out into a container using a submersible pump.  The content of the container was inspected and remaining liquid was removed from the rolloff and placed into drums.  Waste generated from the cleanup was disposed of as hazardous waste.
column169: GLOBAL FOUNDRIES has updated their procedures for this task to implement better checks for the presence of free liquid in the roll off prior to offering the material for shipment in commerce.  These checks will be performed throughout the process of filling the container and a final check immediately prior to removal of the container from the building for loading.  GLOBAL FOUNDRIES will ensure that individuals participating in this task in the future have been appropriately trained to the new procedure steps.

column168: Driver was driving on HWY 79 when he saw the rear wash out cap disconnect. Product splashed onto the trailer surface. The driver stopped on the highway shoulder. The driver did not have another cap. The Miller Emergency Response team from El Dorado, AR responded to inspect the washout port, replace the cap and to remove product which was on the exterior of the trailer. A small amount reach the pavement where he was parked. That was also removed by the response team.     We believe the cause of the cap failure was the cap was cross threaded onto the washout port after the tank was cleaned and the cap replace to it's closed position.
column169: The tank truck industry has started to remove or close these ports which are a source of spills and leaks. This is through the efforts of the Cargo Tank Risk Management Committee research to determine if the ports are needed for cleaning the interiors of the cargo tanks.

column168: On March 23, 2016 at 1532 ET, Superior Bulk Logistics called in regards to a release that occurred on March 19, 2016 at 1230 ET. A tanker (3372) containing molten sulfur had undergone a mechanical failure, releasing approximately 50-pounds of sulfur to the asphalt roadway. The driver was driving from the Golf Sulfur Plant, when the vent of the tanker malfunctioned causing the release. The driver drove approximately 1250 ft, leaving a thin sulfur splatter trail that is about 1250 x 2 ft. A contractor was dispatched who used a sandblaster to remove the solidified sulfur off the asphalt road way. All debris and impacted materials were swept up and placed into a (1) 55-gallon steel drum which was taken off site for disposal.

A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the driver's post trip inspection, it was discovered that approximately 1 cup  of material had  escaped from a thin crack that had developed in the side of the container. The driver put down absorbent pads, cleaned up the spill and proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable over-pack drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

ECS CLERK BROUGHT IT TO THE ATTENTION OF HAZMAT AUDITOR. ONLINE SEARCH SHOWED MSDS CLASSIFIED PRODUCT AS: UN1263, PAINT, PG II, WITH EXCEPTIONS FOR LIMITED QUANTITY/ORM-D. NO OUTER MARKINGS OR INDICATORS OF HAZMAT ON THE OUTER CARTON. HMSC CONTACTED: TREAT AS UNDECLARED   HOLD PENDING REGULATORY INVESTIGATION. REFERENCE #011036 - LES.

CALLED TO THE PD-9 FOR A PACKAGE THAT WAS TORN AND MERCHANDISE STARTING TO FALL OUT. PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP WORK AREA TO BE REBOXED. UPON REBOXING, THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN 10 AEROSOL CANS. PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS INDICATING THAT IT CONTAINED AEROSOL CANS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. CALLED HMSC AND TALKED TO ROBIN AND WAS TOLD TO TAKE 6 SIDED PHOTOS AND SEND TO ADG COMPLIANCE, ENTER INTO ETT, AND HOLD PACKAGE.

column168: A trailer unloading UN1830 Sulfuric acid from a 55 gal poly drum reported a 25 gallon release due to a forklift puncture by terminal personnel. The spill was cleaned up by hazmat contractors and all waste was taken offsite pending disposal.

During unloading activities, it was discovered that 1-55 gallon steel drum was punctured apparently by a forklift and resulted in the release of 1 gallon of UN1993 Flammable liquids, n.o.s. (Isopropanol). Terminal personnel over packed the damaged drum and staged it on site pending shipper instructions.

The employee was loading his bobtail at the service unit. When he was finished loading he took the hose off and laid it down on the back of the bobtail. He went to get the meter reading from the tank and when he got back into the bobtail he forgot the hose was still on the back of it. when he moved the bobtail the hose got caught on the bumper and pulled the hose off the bulk head causing 3 gallons of propane to release into the air. There was no damage to the bobtail.
column169: Additional safety training for all employees.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: While offloading an intermediate bulk container (IBC) at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI, it was observed to have a small leak. Upon investigating, it was determined to contain three articles containing poly-chlorinated biphenyl contaminated oil. The articles were not secure within the IBC and tipped over while in transit. This caused oil to be released from the articles and approximately one pint was release onto the steel lined truck floor. The spilled oil was absorbed with clay absorbent which was then added to the IBC. In addition, the surface area of the spill was decontaminated with diesel fuel and swipe tests were analyzed to determine the area had no residual PCB contamination.
column169: In order to prevent a reoccurance of this event, the field personnel received additional training on appropriate packaging for articles containing polychlorinated biphenyl contaminated oil. Included in the training was the need to ensure all articles are properly secured to prevent them from tipping over and to provide a means of secondary containment in case they should develop a leak.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE TRAILER, TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND SDS WAS REVIEWED. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INSPECTION, FIVE CARDBOARD BOXES WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED AT NOSE OF TRAILER. EACH BOX CONTAINED ONE 5-GALLON PLASTIC BAG. ONE 5-GALLON PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING, AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT TO THE PALLET AND TRAILER FLOOR. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED BOXES INTO ONE 55-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED ON THE FREE LIQUID, AND FLOOR AND PALLET WERE NEUTRALIZED. SPENT ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM, ALONG WITH DAMAGED BOXES, WHICH WAS LEFT ON TRAILER, PENDING DISPOSITION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OF EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ROADRUNNER TRANSPORTATION WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND RIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: HYDRITE CHEMICAL CO. WAS THE CARRIER TRANSPORTING SEVERAL TOTES AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS TO OUR CUSTOMER, WHO WAS THE SHIPPER, TO THE SHIPPERS RECEIVING LOCATION AT 551 KIMBERLY DRIVE, CAROL STREAM, ILLINOIS.    APPROXIMATELY 4 MILES FROM THE LOCATION, OUR DRIVER, GREG DUNFORD,  WAS CUT-OFF BY A VEHICLE WHO CAME FROM THE REAR RIGHT, MOVED TO THE REAR LEFT, SPED UP AND PULLED IN FRONT OF THE TRAILER AT A STOP LIGHT.   OUR DRIVER HIT THE BRAKES TO AVOID A COLLISION.   HE DID NOT FEEL A SHIFT IN THE LOAD, NOR DID HE HEAR ANYTHING, THOUGH HE DID LOOK BEHIND HIM FOR EVIDENCE OF SKID MARKS.   HE LOOKED AND DID NOT SEE SKID MARKS OR ANY LIQUID.    THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION AT 551 KIMBERLY DRIVE.   HE PULLED FORWARD TO THE RIGHT, AND THEN BACKED IN OVER A HUMP AND DOWN THE CONTAINMENT DOCK.   HE WALKED AROUND THE FRONT OF HIS TRUCK TOWARDS THE DOCK, AND THE CUSTOMER HAD ALREADY OPENED THE OVERHEAD DOOR.   THE CUSTOMER NOTICED SOME DRIPS WHICH STARTED TO LEAK MORE AS THE DRIVER WAS WALKING UP AND TOLD THE DRIVER.   THE DRIVER PULLED FORWARD TO CHANGE THE PITCH OF THE TRAILER, AND PUT SOME CONTAINERS UNDER THE CORNERS OF THE TRAILER.   SIMULTANEOUSLY, THE CUSTOMER LAID NUMEROUS BAGS OF FLOOR DRY ON THE SPILLED MATERIAL, ON THE DOCK AREA AND ON TOP OF THE SEWER COVER.   ONCE THE TRAILER WAS PULLED FORWARD, THE RELEASE WAS LARGELY DRIPS INTO CONTAINERS FROM THE CORNERS OF THE TRAILER.   THE LIQUID APPEARED TO BE LARGELY CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER.    THE DRIVER CALLED THE HYDRITE PLANT TO NOTIFY US OF THE RELEASE.   CHRIS KRUK, HYDRITE WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR, CALLED TO PROTECTIVELY REPORT THE SPILL TO THE NRC.   TERRY FONS AND DAVE KRESS, REGIONAL OPERATIONS MANAGER, CALLED R3 ENVIRONMENTAL TO HAVE THEM RESPOND TO THE SPILL.    R3 INITIATED MOBILIZATION AND CALLED HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORP.  TO ASSIST IN THE RELEASE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP DUE TO THEIR PROXIMITY.    THERE WAS NO OBSERVED LIQUID ON KIMBERLY DRIVE.    R3 WAS ON SITE AT 10:33 AM.    THEY DISCUSSED THE MATERIALS ON THE BOL, THE SDSS AND TESTED THE PH OF THE MATERIAL, WHICH WAS ALKALINE.   THERE WERE NO FREE LIQUIDS IN THE ABSORBANT PLACED ON THE CONCRETE DOCK.  THEY FIRST CLEANED UP THE ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND PUT IT INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM.   NEXT THEY EXPOSED A STORM SEWER CROCK IN THE DOCK AREA THAT HAD BEEN COVERED BY A DRAIN MAT AND THE CLAY ABSORBANT.   THE STANDING LIQUID WAS BELOW THE DRAIN OUTLET PIPE IN THE BASIN.  THE PH WAS > 13 S.U.   THE RESPONDERS THEN CHECKED THE ADJACENT DOWNSTREAM STORM WATER BASIN, ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE DOCK, AND IT HAD A PH OF 7.  IT DID NOT APPEAR THAT ANY MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE STORM SEWER.    THE RESPONDERS CALLED IN A VACUUM TRUCK TO EMPTY THE DOWNSTREAM BASIN, THE DOCK BASIN AND TO REMOVE THE LIQUID IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.    UPON DONNING PPE AND ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER, THE RESPONDERS NOTED THAT LIQUID HAD ACCUMULATED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.   THEY WORKED AT SCRAPING UP SOLID PRECIPITATE FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.   IT WAS N
column169: THE WAREHOUSE PERSON AND THE DRIVER WERE EACH GIVEN DISCIPLINARY ACTION FOR INFREQUENTLY PREPARING THE SHIPMENT FOR TRANSPORT. IN ADDITION, ALTERNATE DUNNAGE IS BEING INVESTIGATED THAT WILL ENHANCE SECUREMENT WITHOUT ADDING AS MUCH WEIGHT.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX WAS DISCOVERED TO BE ODOROUS DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AND WAS SET ASIDE AND HELD. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS SOME TYPE OF AIRCRAFT PART INSIDE THE BOX WHICH HAD APPARENTLY NOT BEEN CLEANED BEFORE SHIPPING. WILLIAM CLARK OF THE SFO/FAA WAS CONTACTED AT 16:25 CDT ON 3-31-2016 TO ADVISE OF THE INCIDENT SO THAT SOMEONE COULD INVESTIGATE. THE PACKAGE WAS TO BE HELD AND LATER PICKED UP BY THE SHIPPER AFTER THE INVESTIGATION WAS FINISHED.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORT. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS A LEAKING BATTERY WAS FOUND. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FORM THE SHIPPER WHICH IDENTIFIED THE ITEM AS UN 2794. IATA/ICAO REGULATIONS HAVE A BATTERIES WET FILLED WITH ACID PROPER SHIPPING NAME WHICH CORRELATES TO THIS UN NUMBER. THE MSDS WAS AN OLDER WHICH ONLY LISTED THE DOT CLASSIFICATION NO THE IATA/ICAO CLASSIFICATION. AS THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOOD MARKINGS, DG LABELS NOR WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED OR HIDDEN DG. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: CARRIER AT CONSIGNEE TO OFF LOAD, WENT TO EXTERNAL VALVE TO REMOVED CAM LOCK, PRODUCT SPRAYED ON GROUND AND HANDS, LEGS AND FACE AND PUT CAM LOCK BACK ON. CARRIER WASHED OFF AND CHANGED CLOTHES. CARRIER MECHANIC FOUND THE DISC HOLDER AND STEAM ASSEMBLE HAD HARDEN PRODUCT WHICH WOULD NOT ALLOW THE VALVE TO CLOSE. THE PRODUCT HARDEN DUE TO THE BALL VALVE OPENED AND THE PLUG MISSING. CARRIER TERMINAL CLEANED AND REPLACED PLUG. CARRIER IS OK AND FEELS FINE.     EVENT 50016

column168: A trailer unloading boxes containing 4 - 1 gal steel pails of UN1263 paint reported a 3 gal release onto the trailer floor. Environmental contractors were dispatched for cleanup and over-packed all damaged products and took for disposal.

Apparently other freight fell on top of the boxes and crushed them. The damaged containers were placed into a drum along with the spill cleanup debris and staged at the terminal pending shipper instructions.

During unloading activities, one 330 gallon poly tote containing UN3082 Environmentally hazardous substances was discovered with a cracked cap releasing approximately 1 liquid gallon of material to the trailer floor. A contractor responded and applied absorbents to the release. The impacted absorbents were placed into a 55 gallon drum which was staged onsite pending disposition. The damaged tote was left onsite pending response by the shipper. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WET IN THE SMALL SORT INDUCTION AREA OF SLS. PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY THE SUPERVISOR. THE AREA WAS RESTRICTED ACCESS AND A DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED. THE RESPONDER RESPONDED TO THE SPILL USING THE DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEETS AND NECESSARY PPE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE SPILL IT WAS DETERMINED THE MATERIAL WAS A PROHIBITED UNDECLARED HAZMAT. AFTER DETERMINING THE MATERIAL WAS PROHIBITED THE CHAIN OF COMMAND WAS FOLLOWED. THE RESPONDER SECURED THE AREA FOLLOWING THE DECISION AND RESPONSE SHEET. AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAS BROUGHT IN TO CLEAN UP AND PROCESS THE SPILLED THE SPILLED MATERIAL.

column168: While staged on dock a pail was punctured by a piece of a wooden pallet which consequently led to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the punctured pail.

column25: Ashland Speciality Ingredients affiliate of Ashland Inc.
column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler found a pallet with drums on it. One of the drums was overhanging the pallet it was staged on and as a result it rubbed against the wooded pallet next to it and consequently created a small hole in the drum contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the abraded drum.
column169: Make sure drums are not overhanging on pallets to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Our driver was traveling through shipper facility to exit and a shipper employee noticed product leaking from top of CTMV onto side. Shipper does not allow our driver near the CTMV while inside their facility. Carrier dispatched a mechanic to the shipper location who found the pressure relief valve to be leaking and replaced with new valve to stop the leak.     Event # 50247

While unloading freight from trailer forklift operator misjudged the clearances of his forkblades and struck a drum staged on a pallet puncturing it and contributing to the unintentional release.Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the punctured drum.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forkblades to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On March 16th, 2016 at approximately 16:30 PST, WUTC MP+E inspector found the BN 875110 with fresh residue on the top and sides of the tank car.  The car was isolated by BNSF and local forces contacted the shipper to respond and inspect the car. The car had just been pulled from the facility and moved only a short distance for staging. The shipper inspected the car and found that the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight. Shipper properly secured the manway housing and wiped clean the residue from the car. Release estimates are based upon information received from shipper. Once cleaned and secured, the shipment was again released into transportation.
column169: The shipper should ensure that personnel responsible for loading tank cars are properly trained and understand their duties to ensure that packages are properly secured prior to being offered into transportation.

column4: A specification cargo tank 1,000 gallons or greater containing any hazardous materials that (1) received structural damage to the lading retention system or damage that requires repair to a system int
column168: After completing a partial unload of approximately 8000 gallons from tank car.  The hazmat employee closed the tank car bottom outlet valve to clear material from hose and pump into tank truck.  The tank car bottom outlet valve didn’t feel or appear to close completely to the hazmat employee.  The hazmat employee was unable to clear the hose or pump indicating that the tank car bottom valve was not closed completely allowing material to continue to flow from tank car through the hose and pump.  The facility uses dry disconnect load connections and was able to safety disconnect from the tank truck while still connected to tank car.  There was approximately 21,000 gallons in tank car.  The shipper was notified and dispatched three trucks to complete the unload of material from tank car.    The tank car was completely unloaded and the unload connections removed from tank car.  The tank car bottom outlet cap was replaced tool tight without incident.      Rescar was called by shipper to elevate the tank car and make the necessary repairs to bottom outlet valve.  Rescar personnel was able to repair tank car by tighten two packing nuts.

A 5 gallon steel pail of UN1993 ethanol arrived at the R&L carriers terminal in Piedmont, SC damaged. It was apparent that the pail was dented by other freight due to a lack of blocking and bracing. Approximately 1 cup of the material released to the plastic shrink wrap.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and over pack the drum.  The 5 gallon pail was over packed into a 55 gallon drum and staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.

column168: ON MARCH 8, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 A.M. CST, A TANKER-TRUCK OPERATED BY CTL TRANSPORTATION, LLC, WAS PARKED AT 6635 JOHN RALSTON ROAD IN HOUSTON, TEXAS, WHEN SITE PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A LEAK COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF GLYCIDYL METHACRYLATE LATE HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE TANK. AT APPROXIMATELY 8:10 A.M. CST, MS. JOAN PFEIFFER OF CTL RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, LC (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL SAFETY AND HEALTH OF HOUSTON (ES&H) TO ASSESS THE SITE AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. THE CREW FROM ES&H MOBILIZED TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW ASSESSED THE TANKER AND DETERMINED THAT THE FRONT AND BACK WASHOUT CAPS HAD AN EXTRA GASKET, CAUSING A GAP IN THE SEAL. THE CREW REMOVED AND REPLACED THE GASKET AND CAPS. THE TANK WAS THEN WIPED DOWN WITH CHEMICAL PADS. ONCE NO FURTHER ACTIONS WERE DEEMED NECESSARY, THE CREW FROM ES&H DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO ENSURE PROPER GASKET AMOUNTS ARE USED.

column168: 10 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL SPILLED ON TO THE ASPHALT STREET AND SHOULDER SOIL WHEN THE HOSE REEL SWITCH OF THE TANK WAGON GOT STUCK IN THE ON POSITION AND THE HOSE NOZZLE VALVE WAS OPENED AS THE NOZZLE STRUCK THE REEL. THE OIL WAS RELEASED FOR ABOUT 10 SECONDS UNTIL THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT THE VALVE OFF. THE DRIVER USED HIS SPILL KIT BOOMS TO TRY TO CONTAIN THE OIL AND SPEEDY DRY TO ABSORB AS MUCH AS HE COULD UNTIL THE CLEAN UP VENDOR ARRIVED.
column169: WE WILL REVIEW THE ISSUE WITH OUR DRIVERS AND STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF CLOSING INTERNAL VALVES TO MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT OF POTENTIAL SPILLAGE.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: AUTOZONE TEAM DRIVERS WERE OUTBOUND ON I-40 NEAR WINSLOW AZ. DRIVER LOST CONTROL, THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY, OVERTURNED & STOPPED ON ITS SIDE BLOCKING ALL EASTBOUND LANES OF I-40. TWO OTHER TRACTOR-TRAILERS STRUCK THE UNDERSIDE OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER. BOTH AUTOZONE TEAM DRIVERS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE LITTLE COLORADO MEDICAL FACILITY IN WINSLOW, AZ. THE MAJORITY OF THE RETAIL CARGO INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS UNDAMAGED. A TOWING VENDOR WAS DISPATCHED TO CLEAR THE ROADWAY. 3E COMPANY/HEPACO, INC. REQUESTED ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICES  THROUGH LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR (RED J ENVIRONMENTAL CORP OR "RED J"). RED J ARRIVED AT 0930 & MET WITH TRAVIS QUALLS, ARIZONA DEPT OF CHEMICALS. OTHER RED J TECHS ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 1200. MOST CARGO WAS UNDAMAGED, BUT IN THE MIDDLE OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER, THERE WERE NUMEROUS DAMAGED & EMPTY OF MOTOR OIL, ANTIFREEZE, WINDSHIELD WIPER FLUID, FUEL ADDITIVES, AEROSOL CANS, LEAKING BATTERIES & CARDBOARD BOXES WET WITH OIL AND OTHER LIQUIDS. (ESTIMATED SPILLAGE OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL IS 1.5 GALLONS) UNDAMAGED CARGO WAS PALLETIZED OR LOADED INTO WIRE CRATES, LOADED ON A RED J CARGO TRAILER & TAKEN TO AUTOZONE'S DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN TOLLESON, AZ FOR INSPECTION & RETURN TO INVENTORY OR RECYCLE. DAMAGED/LEAKING BATTERIES & RETAIL CHEMICALS WERE SECURED IN INDIVIDUAL HEAVY-DUTY PLASTIC BAGS WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, SEALED & PLACED INTO THE RED J CARGO TRAILER FOR AUTOZONE'S DISTRIBUTION CENTER. WE CARDBOARD AND DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN A ROLL OF CONTAINER BY RED J. THE TRACTOR WAS UPRIGHTED AT 1700 & REMOVED BY TRI-R TOWING. RED J REPORTED AN ESTIMATED 0 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL LEAKED FROM THE FUEL TANKS ON THE OVERTURNED TRACTOR SADDLE TANKS. RED J WAS DIRECTED BY ADOT TO REMOVE SMALL AREAS OF STAINED SOIL BY HAND EXCAVATION (1-2"). ONCE ALL VISUALLY STAINED SOIL WAS REMOVED, RED J APPLIED A MICRO BIOLOGICAL AGENT TO NATURALLY DEGRADE ANY RESIDUAL FUEL CONTAMINATION. EXCAVATED SOIL WAS PLACED INTO THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER & REMOVED FROM THE SCENE ON MARCH 18TH & TRANSPORTED TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT OF ARIZONA, PAINTED DESERT SUBTITLE D LANDFILL FACILITY NEAR JOSEPH, CITY ARIZONA FOR DISPOSAL (TICKET #169790).
column169: AUTOZONE WILL INCLUDE A SCENARIO SIMILAR TO THE SITUATION DESCRIBED IN VI, IN ITS TRAINING CURRICULUM FOR MANAGERS AND DRIVERS ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAINTAINING ATTENTIVENESS AND AVOIDING DRIVER DISTRACTIONS DURING ITS TRAINING RELATED TO DRIVER SAFETY. THE DRIVER IS NO LONGER AN EMPLOYEE OF AUTOZONE.

column168: WHILE AT THE PRECOAT METALS FACILITY, A NEW 55 GALLON PAIN DRUM (1A2) ESTIMATED TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PAINT WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT ON THE SIDE NEAR THE BOTTOM DURING IN HOUSE TRANSFER OF THE PAIN DRUMM TO ITS DESIGNATE STORAGE AREA. THE DRUM WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND AN ESTIMATED 47 GALLON OF PAINT REMAINING IN THE CONTAINER WAS TRANSFERRED IN A NEW CONTAINER. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PAINT WAS SPILLED AT PRECOAT FACILITY DUE TO THE PUNCTURE. BASED ON THE ESTIMATED QUANTITY OF PAINT RELEASED TO THE DRUM WAS SUBSEQUENTLY LOADED ON A TRAILER USED SPECIFICALLY FOR TRANSPORT OF EMPTY CONTAINERS. THE TRAILER WAS PICKED UP BY MEYER DRUM INC FOR RECONDITION AND RECYCLING.   DURING TRANSIT THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS STOPPED FOR A FAULTY BRAKE LIGHT BY AN INDIAN STATE POLICE OFFICER. THE OFFICER PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE CARGO AND NOTICED WHITE PAINT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS VERIFIED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARGO AREA OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE AND WAS NOT RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE TRUCK DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS HOME OFFICE WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY NOTIFIED PRECOAT METALS. MEYER DRUM COMPANY DISPATCHED THEIR SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WITH OVER PACK DRUM AND SPILL CLEANING MATERIALS. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND ASSOCIATED DEBRIS FROM THE CLEANUP OF THE PAINT MATERIALS WAS PLACED IN A 85 GALLON OVER PACK FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: PRECOAT METALS DISCUSSED THE INCIDENT WITH PLANT EMPLOYEES AND RE-TRAINED THEM IN THE PROPER HANDLING AND MANAGEMENT OF EMPTY CONTAINERS INCLUDING VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER TO ENSURE THE CONTAINER IS EMPTY. EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN RE-TRAINED TO ENSURE DAMAGED CONTAINERS ARE NOT OFFERED FOR SHIPPING. THE PLANT EMPTY CONTAINER MANAGEMENT PROCEDURE HAS BEEN UPDATED TO ENSURE ALL CONTAINERS THAT PREVIOUSLY HELD A MATERIAL MEETING THE DEFINITION OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AS DEFINED BY THE US DOT SHALL BE SHIPPED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR172.203(E).

column168: There was no actual package failure. Our driver began the offloading process at the consignee location and the consignee's connection to their storage tank began to leak product. column168: A Veolia employee was using a drum cart to move 2 drums containing regulated medical waste on the truck and loading dock at the Veolia 10-day in transit facility. The drum cart was not properly placed under the poly drum causing the metal fork to puncture the bottom of the drum. A small pin hole leak was caused by the metal fork of the drum cart resulting in the release of approximately 1 pint of liquid to the sealed concrete floor of the Veolia warehouse. The drum was placed onto its side and over-packed into a salvage drum. All material was re-mediated and cleaned up with a hospital grade disinfectant. All cleanup material was placed into the overpack DOT rated salvage drum.
column169: Veolia employees were retrained on proper use of drum carts and drum moving equipment. They were also trained to inspect equipment before each use to ensure no defects are identified.

column168: ON MARCH 13 2016 AT 10:30PM AN MPC TRANSPORT TRAILER LOADED WITH GASOLINE (TRAILER 35205) WAS STRUCK BY A PASSENGER VEHICLE ON HOLTON ROAD DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF MPC NORTH MUSKEGON TERMINAL. THE TRANSPORT DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED THE VEHICLE AND CALLED 911. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED BY THE OCCUPANT OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE. THE MPC DRIVER OBSERVED THAT GASOLINE WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRANSPORT LOADING HEADS ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND NOTIFIED TERMINAL PERSONNEL. THE AREA WAS CLEARED UNTIL EMERGENCY CREWS ARRIVED. WHO CLOSED HOLTON ROAD TO VEHICULAR TRAFFIC IN BOTH DIRECTIONS. ONCE IT WAS DEEMED SAFE TO ENTER THE SCENE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL AND ONSITE TRANSPORT DRIVERS IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOM AT THE ACCIDENT SITE AS WELL AS ALONG THE DOWN GRADIENT CURB TO THE SOUTHWEST ALONG HOLTON ROAD. THE TERMINAL OIL SPILL RESPONSE ORGANIZATION (OSRO) NORTHERN A -1 ENVIRONMENTAL WAS NOTIFIED AND DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL RESOURCES TO THE SITE. THE TRANSPORT WAS MOVED FOR THE ROAD TO LANE 4 TERMINAL LOADING RACK FOR THE REMOVAL OF REMAINING PRODUCT IN IS COMPARTMENTS. THE PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, TRAILER 35205 WAS PUMPED OFF USING A THIRD PARTY TRUCK. COMPARTMENT NOS 4 AND 5 WERE PUMPED INTO THE THIRD PARTY TRUCK AND DELIVERED TO A SERVICE STATION. COMPARTMENT NOS 1 AND 2 WERE PUMPED TO A TERMINAL ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. TRANSPORT TRAILER 35205 WAS MADE SAFE FOR TRAVEL TO A REPAIR SHOP.
column169: FOLLOWING MPC PROCEDURES, THE MPC DRIVER WAS SENT FOR POST-ACCIDENT DRUG SCREEN. IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE RELEASE, THE DRIVER RESPONDED TO THE SITUATION AS HE HAD BEEN TRAINED. THIS ACCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WIDELY AT MPC SAFETY MEETINGS IN THE FOLLOWING DAYS IN ORDER TO COMMUNICATE LESSONS LEARNED TO ALL MPC TRANSPORT DRIVERS AND TERMINAL PERSONNEL. IN ORDER TO INCREASE PREPAREDNESS FOR FUTURE SIMILAR RELEASE EVENTS, SPILL DRILLS AND BOOM DEPLOYMENT EXERCISES WILL CONTINUE TO BE HELD AT THE NORTH MUSKEGON TERMINAL. CONTINUED EFFORTS TO BUILD A WORKING RELATIONSHIP WITH LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS WILL IMPROVE THE ABILITY OF LOCAL FIRST RESPONDERS TO EFFECTIVELY RESPOND TO TRANSPORT ACCIDENTS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE STATEMENT FROM THE DRIVER, DUE TO ISSUES WITH THE PUMPING SYSTEM HE HAD AVAILABLE ON HIS TRUCK, HE TOOK THE INITATIVE TO TRANSFER USING COMPRESSED AIR FROM THE TRUCK BRAKE RESERVIOR TO PRESSURIZE THE IBC. THIS WAS THE FRIST OF TWO IBC'S TO BE TRNSFERRED INTO THE CUSTOMER STRAGE TANK. HE ATTACHED ONE END OF HIS 3/8'' AUR HOSE TO THE AIR BRAKE RESERVIOR ON HIS TRUCK WHICH HAD A QUARTER TURN VALVE AND FEMALE QUICK DISCONNECT FITTING AND THE OTHER END TO A FITTING QITH A MALE QUICK DISCONNECT HE INSTALLED ON THE TOP OF THE 330 GALLON ULTRATAINER (STANDARD PRESSURE) IBC. HE THEN CONNECTED A 1 1/2" TRANSFER HOSE FROM THE FITTING AT THE IBC TO THE FILL LINE ON THE CUSOTMERS STORAGE TANK. HE OPNED THE VALVE ON THE CUSTOMER TANK THEN THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE IBC. HE THEN OPENED THAT AIR VALVE AT THE AIR BRAKE RESERVIOR SLIGHTLY (HE STARTED THAT HE THOUGHT THIS WOULD RESULT IN ABOUT 3 PSI OF AIR PRESSURE) HE POSITIONED HIMSELF AT THE PASSENGER DOOR AREA OF HIS TUCK. THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO TRANSFER, AFTER APPROXIMATELY 290 GALLONS WERE TRANSFERRRED HE HEARD A LOUND NOISE AND THE TRUCK SHOOT AND NOTICE THE IBC HAD FAILED. THE CUSTOMER CAME TO THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRUCK FROM THE REAR AS OUR DRIVER CAME TO THE DRIVERSIDE OF THE TRUCK FROM THE FRONT, HE THEN SHUT THE AIR VALVE AND WALKED AROUND THE FRONT OF THE TUCK TO SHUT THE VALVE ON THE CUSTOMER TANK. HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVIOSR OF THE INCIDENT AND WAIT FOR HIM TO ARRIVE. THE USE OF UNREGULATED COMPRESSED AIR TO PRESSUIZE AN IBC WOULD HAVE NOT BEEN AUTHORIXE BY THE COMPANY. THE DRIVER WAS SUPENDED FOR 3 DAYS AND TEMPORALLY RELOACTED TO A WAREHOUSE FUNCTION FOR FUTHER EVALUATION

ON MARCH 19, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 P.M. CDT, A TANKER TRUCK OPERATED BY CTL TRANSPORTATION, LLC WAS TRAVELING ON THE ON RAMP TO 1-10 FROM FL-77 IN CHIPLEY, FLORIDA, WHEN THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAK FROM THE TANK. THE DRIVER MANEUVERED THE VEHICLE TO THE ROADSIDE SHOULDER AND CAME TO A STOP. THE DRIVER DISCOVERED LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF TURPENTINE HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE DOME LID OF THE TANK TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE ROADWAY. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 P.M. CDT, MR. RANDY DIETER OF CTL RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, LC (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE ON THEIR BEHALF. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES(SWS) TO ASSESS THE SITE AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. THE CREW FROM SWS MOBILIZED TO THE LOCATION. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW ASSESSED THE TANK AND CONFIRMED A MISFIT GASKET CAUSED THE LEAK WHILE IN TRANSPORT. ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO WIPE AND CLEAN THE TANK ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO COLLECT RELEASED TURPENTINE ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL. THE CREW THEN PLACED ABSORBENT PADS IN THE TANK'S DRAIN TUBES AND ESCORTED THE UNIT TO THE NEAREST GAS STATION. THE UNIT WAS STAGED AT THE GAS STATION UNTIL A FITTED GASKET COULD BE OBTAINED. ONCE NO ADDITIONAL ACTIONS WERE CONSIDERED NECESSARY, THE CREW FROM SWS DEMOBILIZED FROM THE SITE.

THE OUTER BOX HAD NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFO OPR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE PAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO HAZMAT MANAGER GARY MOHR. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: CONSOLIDATED CARGO WAS RECEIVED FROM LAX FOR CONTINUED LINE TO PPG. THE CONSOLIDATED CARGO WAS BEING RE-PACKED FOR SHIPMENT IN DIFFERENT CONTAINERS APPROPRIATE FOR THE AIRCRAFT FLIGHT PPG. THE SHIPPER IS A TSA APPROVED INDIRECT AIR CARRIER IAC (FREIGHT FORWARDER). THE CARGO WAS PRE-SCREENED BY A TSA APPROVED CERTIFIED CARGO SCREENING FACILITY (CCSF).     WHILE BEING RE-PACKED, UNDECLARED HAZMAT WAS FOUND AS SUMMARIZED BELOW:      * MASTER AWB: 173 LAX 1141-1444     * DATED 17 MARCH 2016     * 111 PIECES CONSOLIDATION SHIPMENT 11,717 KG      * HOUSE AWB #S00053532 16P SHIPS SPARES IN TRANSIT 312 KG. (CONTAINING NON-SPILLABLE        BATTERY UN2800).      * HOUSE AWB #S00053612 8P AUTO PARTS 105 KG. (CONTAINING SPRAWAY - SUPER FLASH SPRAY ADHESIVE UN1950)    AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY, FAA WAS CONTACTED TO REPORT THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT AND TO PROVIDE FAA A COPY OF THE MASTER AWB AS WELL AS A COPY OF THE HOUSE AWBs FOR CARGO CONTAINING THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT. THE CARGO WAS HELD UNTIL FAA APPROVAL WAS OBTAINED TO TRANSPORT THE NON-HAZMAT CARGO TO PPG. THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT WAS RETAINED AT HA CARGO PENDING FAA DIRECTION. AFTER FAA PROVIDED APPROVAL TO RELEASE THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT. HA PROVIDED THE HAZMAT TO SHIPPER'S AUTHORIZED AGENTS IN HNL. FAA CONDUCTED FOLLOW-UP INTERVIEWS WITH THE CARGO AGENTS THAT IDENTIFIED THE HAZMAT AS THEY WERE RE-PACKING THE THE CONSOLIDATED CARGO FOR THE FLIGHT TO PPG.
column169: INCLUDE A "NO HAZMAT" AND A "HAZMAT" BOX TO BE CHECKED ON THE MASTER AWB. IF THE HAZMAT BOX IS CHECKED, THE CONSOLIDATED SHIPMENT CONTAINS A HAZMAT MATERIAL. THE HOUSE AWB CONTAINING THE HAZMAT MUST BE LISTED UNDER THE CHECKED "HAZMAT" BOX SO THAT THE PACKAGING/LABELING CAN BE VERIFIED.

column168: 3/29/16: BNSF Denver IMF operations reported that the above trailer arrived intrain with evidence that a liquid substance had leaked from within. Due to this LTL shipment containing listed as hazmat the unit was immediately parked in the safe haven containment zone. Shipper YRC was notified through their response service ERTS who called out Custom Environmental Services for containment and cleanup. CES reported that after unloading surrounding cargo, they located a 55 gallon poly drum that contained Hydrobromic Acid UN1788, hazard class 8, PG II that had leaked. The leakage was sloshing of the product through an improperly installed bung cap on top of the drum. It is estimated that between 2 and 3 gallons of product was lost. The drum cap was reinstalled, all affected surfaces were cleaned and cargo reloaded.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING NORTH ON US HWY 71 ABOUT 60 MPH AND REAR ENDED A KENWORTH SERVICE TRUCK EXITING THE HIGHWAY. OUR TRUCK CLIPPED THE REAR, DRIVER'S SIDE CORNER OF THEIR TRUCK. THE IMPACT TORE AWAY THE FRONT, PASSENGER SIDE OF OUR TRUCK BODY AND CAUSED OUR SIDE DOORS TO BE DISLODGED FROM THE TRUCK, ENABLING BATTERIES TO BE SCATTERED. THE IMPACT ALSO CAUSED OUR TRUCK TO ROLLOVER ONTO ITS SIDE AND SKID DOWN THE HWY. THIS CAUSED MANY BATTERIES TO BE ON THEIR SIDE AND LEAKED ACID ONTO THE HWY UNTIL THE TRUCK WAS UP-RIGHTED. THE RELEASE BEGAN THE MOMENT THE CRASH HAPPENED AND LASTED UNTIL THE TRUCK WAS UP-RIGHTED (APPROX. 1 HOUR).IN ORDER TO MAINTAIN THE SPILL, ALL DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE PLACED IN HEAVY PLASTIC BAGS FOR SAFE TRANSPORT. ALSO, ACID NEUTRALIZER WAS SPREAD ON THE ROAD, WHEREVER THE ACID HAD LEAKED ON THE HWY. ALSO, ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING WAS GIVEN TO THIS DRIVER SO THAT SIMILAR INCIDENTS WILL NOT OCCUR AGAIN.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: DRIVER OFF LOADED UN-LEAD INTO THE PREMIUM CAUSING THE DOWNGRADE OF PRODUCT. THIS REQUIRED US TO PUMP OVER THAT TANK INTO THE UNLEADED TANK.     DRIVER WAS PUMPING CONTAMINATED PRODUCT INTO THE UNLEAD TANK AND THE TANK PRESSURED UP WHEN THE CAPACITY OF THE TANK WAS REACHED. AT THAT TIME, THE DRIVER DETACHED THE HOSE CAUSING THE SPILL. THE DRIVER LIFTED THE STINGER OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAMINATED TANK AND THEN HAD THE OTHER DRIVER CLOSE THE VALVE AND TURN OFF THE PUMP. THE HOSE WAS THEN LOOSENED IN ORDER TO MOVE IT OT THE TRUCK TO FINISH PUMPING THE CONTAMINATED PRODUCT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WHEN PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED, CAUSING A SPILL, WHEN THE HOSE WAS LOOSENED. THE HOSE WAS REATTACHED IN AN EFFORT TO CONTAIN FLOWING PRODUCT. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT BETWEEN 100-150 GALLONS WAS RELEASED ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND ALSO ONTO A SMALL DIRT SWELL OWNED BY THE CITY OF PULLMAN. AFTER THE SPILL WAS STOPPED, OUR DRIVER CALLED 911 THEN I WAS CONTACTED AND IN COMMUNICATION THROUGHOUT THE PROCESS.     PLEASE LET ME KNOW IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS.     THANKS,    JON SHEPHERD  NORTHWEST PETROLEUM SERVICES.
column169: WE NOW HAVE A POLICY IN PLACE FOR CONTAMINATION'S. A SUPERVISOR MUST BE ONSITE FOR THE PUMP OUT. TRANSITING PRODUCT FROM THE TANK TO ANOTHER WILL NO LONGER BE ALLOWED. WHEN A CONTAMINATION OCCURS, THE DRIVER MUST PUMP THE PRODUCT BACK INTO THE TRUCK BEFORE IT IS DROPPED AGAIN.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER WHILE HE WAS MAKING THE DELIVERY A PERSON CAME OUT OF THE STATION AND SAID THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM WAS GOING OFF. HE SHUT DOWN AND SAW THE HOSE WAS FILLED WITH GAS AND WAS NOT DRAINING. HE ATTEMPTED TO DRAIN THE HOSE AND THE FITTING POPPED OFF CAUSING GAS TO RELEASE TO THE GROUND. IT WAS RAINING AT THE TIME. THE CUSTOMER REPORTED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GA WAS RELEASED. THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY REPORTED APPROXIMATELY 100 GA WHICH INCLUDED 90% WATER THAT WAS FROM THEIR CLEAN UP AND THE FACT THAT IT WAS RAINING.

column168: DRIVER 1 STATED THAT HE WAS DRIVING VEHICLE 1 SOUTHWEST ON CASEYVILLE ROAD NW. DRIVER 1 STATED THAT AS HE WAS DRIVING VEHICLE 1, THE KNOB, ATTACHED TO THE STEERING WHEEL, GOT CAUGHT IN HIS SHIRT SLEEVE CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF VEHICLE 1. DRIVER 1 STATED THAT VEHICLE 1 RAN PARTIALLY OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND COLLIDED WITH A TRAFFIC SIGN- WHICH INDICATED A STOP SIGN WAS AHEAD. VEHICLE 1 THEN TRAVELED ACROSS THE ROADWAY AND OFF OF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY, RUNNING THROUGH A DITCH, AND COLLIDING WITH A TREE STUMP. THE COLLISION CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 57 GALLONS OF OFF THE ROAD DIESEL TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED AND RESPONDED, INCLUDING EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT CLIFFORD GALEY.
column169: ROAD WAS WET + HAD DEEP SHOULDER W/FRESH MATERIAL ON THE EDGE OF ROAD. OUR DRIVER WAS BLESSED TO WALK AWAY UNHARMED - OUR COMPANY WAS BLESSED WITH NO INJURIES AND NO ONE ELSE INVOLVED.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN COUNTY ROAD 200 WHEN VEHICLE WENT OFF THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT. DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS REACHING FOR A CUP AND WAS DISTRACTED. ONCE DRIVER REALIZED THE SITUATION HE JERKED THE WHEEL TO THE LEFT IN AN ATTEMPT TO BRING THE VEHICLE BACK ON THE ROADWAY. THIS ACTION CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO GO OUT OF CONTROL AND ROLL ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE. THE VEHICLE SLID ON ITS RIGHT SIDE ACROSS THE ROADWAY AND CAME TO REST HALF ON THE ROADWAY AND HALF IN THE DITCH. AMMONIUM NITRATE AND FUEL OIL (DIESEL) WERE RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
column169: EMPLOYEES WILL BE TRAINED ON PROCEDURES OF OFF ROAD RECOVERY, ROLLOVER PREVENTION DEFENSIVE DRIVING, AND BPC EMERGENCY TRANSPORTATION PLAN AS PART OF THE MONTHLY SAFETY TRAINING. THIS IS REQUIRED AS PART OF THE DOT SPECIALIST PERMIT 11579 AND IME SLP 23.

column168: ON MARCH 28, 2016 AT 12:15:00, A US ENVIRONMENTAL DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING FROM HIS TRAILER. THE TRUCK WAS ON EXIT 21 TRAVELING WEST ON I70. DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE ROADSIDE TO INVESTIGATE THE CLAIM AND VERIFY THE LOAD.     DRIVER DID FIND MATERIAL LEAKING AND MADE CALLS TO LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND REPORTED BACK US ENVIRONMENTAL OPERATION REQUESTING FOR CLEANUP RESPONSE. DRIVER PLACE SPILL PADS DOWN IN DIRECT AREA.     AT APPROXIMATELY 13:02 LOCAL AUTHORITIES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. DRIVER ALONG WITH LOCAL AUTHORITIES IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM UN1993, WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS MATERIAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 14:52 THE RESPONSE CLEANUP CREW STARTED TO CLEAN UP.     DURING THE CLEAN UP THE RESPONSE TEAM NOTICED THAT MATERIAL WAS WEEPING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM. NO VISUAL HOLES OR DAMAGE WERE NOTICED AT THE TIME. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVER PACK DRUM, LABELED AND SEALED.     THE CLEANUP LASTED FOR APPROXIMATELY TWO AND HALF HOURS. THE CLEANUP CONSISTED OF THE SURROUNDING AREA, THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND OVER PACKING THE DRUM. THE QUANTITY OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE DRUM WAS APPROXIMATELY 13 GALLONS OF MATERIAL.    THE INCIDENT WAS GIVEN ALL CLEAR BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY.
column169: US ENVIRONMENTAL REVIEWED INTERNAL PROCEDURES TRANSFERS OF MATERIALS OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION.     THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH DRIVERS TO ENSURE THE IMPORTANCE OF INSPECTING LOAD OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION.    COMMUNICATION WITH CUSTOMER ON THE RESPONSIBILITIES WHEN OFFERING LOADS FOR TRANSPORTATION, WORKING WITH CUSTOMER TO DEVELOP A SOP TO INCLUDE AN INSPECTION REPORT FOR SHIPPING MATERIALS.

column168: TRUCK FAILED TO YIELD FOR TRAIN CROSSING WHICH RESULTED IN IT GETTING HIT BY THE TRAIN. THE TRAIN CRACKED PIPING AND BARREL UPON IMPACT. LIQUID BURNED FOR APPROXIMATELY 7 HRS AT THAT POINT PRESSURE WAS RELEASED AND CONTINUED TO BURN, APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR LATER AN EXPLOSION OF THE REMAINING MATERIAL OCCURRED.
column169: INSTALLATION OF CAMERAS ON COMPANY TRUCKS HAS OCCURRED AND MESSAGES, LETTERS, AND TRAINING HAS BEEN SENT AND COMPLETED WITH CHS DRIVERS CONCERNING RAIL CROSSINGS. CONTINUED MONITORING OF DRIVING EVENTS AND RIDE-ALONG'S WILL BE OCCURRING AS WELL.

column168: ON 03/26/16 ACORD TRANSPORTATION DRIVER STEVE HILL WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM PRYOR OK TO WELLDON, IA. WHILE STOPPED AT THE WOODSHED TRUCK STOP IN BIG CABIN, OK, ANOTHER INDIVIDUAL NOTICED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA IN THE VICINITY OF THE TRAILER, YET OUR DRIVER WAS NOT CONFRONTED. IT WAS NOT UNTIL MR. HILL WENT TO LEAVE THE TRUCK STOP THAT HE WAS CONTACTED AND STOPPED BY THE BIG CABIN POLICE. UPON SPEAKING WITH THE OFFER, THE OFFICER INFORMED MR. HILL THAT HE HAD A LEAK BUT WOULD NOT LET MR. HILL (A QUALIFIED COMPETENT, AND TRAINED INDIVIDUAL) TO APPROACH THE TRAILER FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE OFFICER THREATENED TO ARREST MR. HILL IF HE ATTEMPTED TO APPROACH THE TRAILER. INSTEAD, BIG CABIN AND VINITA, OK FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE CONTACTED. UPON ARRIVAL, THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED. THE NUMBER OF INDIVIDUALS IN THE AFFECTED AREA IS UNKNOWN. UPON INVESTIGATION, THE ODOR WAS IDENTIFIED TO BE COMING FROM A SHUT OFF AREA NEAR THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE ALLEGED RELEASE WAS SO MINIMAL THAT YOU HAD TO BE RIGHT AT THE SHUT OFF.    ANOTHER ACORD TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE SCENE WITH THE INTENT OF TRANSFERRING THE PRODUCT INTO IT. THE ACORD TRUCK INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS MOVED TO A SAFER LOCATION AWAY FROM THE TRUCK STOP. THE PRODUCT WAS THEN TRANSFERRED FROM ONE ACORD TRANSPORT TO THE TO OTHER. THIS WAS DONE SAFELY WITH NO LOSS OF PRODUCT.     FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, TRAILER 7122 WAS RETURNED TO ACORD'S FACILITY CHANDLER, OK FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIR IF NEEDED. ALTHOUGH NO VISIBLE DAMAGES WERE OBSERVED ON ANY OF THE TRAILER COMPONENTS, NEW ORINGS WERE INSTALLED IN THE BONNET ASSEMBLY AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.    SEE REPORTS OF RESPONDING AGENCIES FOR VERIFICATION THAT ALLEGED RELEASE WAS SO MINIMAL (IF ANY) THAT IT DID NOT EVEN REQUIRE REPORTING. NO HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT NOR ANY PERSONNEL INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: ACORD TRANSPORTATION, INC. EQUIPMENT IS CONSISTENTLY, CONTINUOUSLY AND THOROUGHLY INSPECTED ON AN ONGOING BASIS TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE AND SAFE OPERATION. THIS PROCESS WILL CONTINUE TO BE DONE. EVEN WITH THIS INCIDENT, WHERE A SLIGHT ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS DETECTED, THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO ANY OF THE EQUIPMENT IDENTIFIED DURING A PAST INCIDENT INSPECTION. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. ANY COMPONENTS THAT COULD HAVE POTENTIALLY RESULTED IN ANY TYPE OF LEAK WERE REPLACED. AS STATED IN THE RESPONDING AGENCIES' REPORTS, NO PRODUCT WAS LOST.

column168: AT 0730 ON MARCH 29, 2016 THE GREENFIELD LOGISTICS DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAKING CONTAINER WHEN HE PULLED INTO ENERGY FUELS RESOURCES INC. (EFR) IN BLANDING, UT. DURING QUESTIONING THE RIVER STATED THAT WHILE TRAVELING NEAR MEEKER, COLORADO, A DEER RAN IN FRONT OF HIM AND HE HAD TO HIT THE BRAKES HARD. THAT WAS THE ONLY TIME DURING THE TRIP THAT THERE HAD BEEN ANY SUDDEN JARRING OF THE LOAD. HE STATED THAT HE HAD FILLED UP WITH FUEL IN RAWLINS, WYOMING AND AT THAT TIME, THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE.     ALL SEALS WERE STILL INTACT THAT WERE INSTALLED PRIOR TO THE CONTAINER LEAVING ORIGIN (DOUGLAS, WY). IT APPEARED THE SHIFT IN THE LOAD DURING TRANSIT CAUSED ENOUGH PRESSURE ON THE LID SEALS TO ALLOW LEAKAGE THROUGH THE SEALS. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS FILLED ABOVE RECOMMENDED LEVELS AND THE MATERIAL WAS MORE LIQUID THAN THE PACKAGE WAS DESIGNED FOR.     AT APPROXIMATELY 094 HOURS THE RSO ALLOWED THE LOAD ONTO THE PROPERTY. THE STATE WAS AWARE OF THE LOADING COMING ONTO PROPERTY. THE MAIN REASON FOR THE LOAD COMING ONTO THE PROPERTY WAS THAT RAIN WAS STARTING TO FALL AND WASHING SOME OF THE MATERIAL OFF OF THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE GROUND. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A LARGER CLEANUP, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO GET INTO THE RESTRICTED AREA.     THE AREA ON US HIGHWAY 191 AND THE EFRI ENTRANCE WAY, WAS WASHED AND MY CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS DUG UP AND TAKEN INTO THE RESTRICTED AREA, AND THEN OUT OF CELL 3. THE AREA WAS SURVEYED AFTER THE RAIN/SNOW HAD STOPPED.
column169: TO PREVENT REOCCURENCE, ADDITIONAL TRAINING WAS PROVIDED ON THE PROPER LOAD LIMITS OF THE PACKAGE AND REQUIREMENTS CLARIFIED FOR LOADING AND TRANSPORT OF LIQUID MATERIAL.

column168: THE CTMV DRIVER HAD JUST LOADED WITH GASOLINE AT A TERMINAL IN BELTON, SC. ALL INDICATIONS ARE THAT, UPON APPROACH TO THE SITE OF THE ACCIDENT, THE DRIVER LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. IT APPEARS THAT THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO KEEP THE TRUCK ON THE ROAD, BUT AFTER COMING BACK ON THE ROAD THE TRAILER OVERTURNED, CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE TANKER THAT RESULTED IN A SPILL AND SUBSEQUENT FIRE. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER BECAME IMMEDIATELY ENGULFED IN FLAMES. IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINED EXACTLY WHERE THE FUEL CAME OUT OF, AS THE CARGO TANK WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED IN THE FIRE. THE BEST WE CAN DETERMINE, THE TANK OVERTURNED ROLLING TO THE RIGHT AND GOUGES OR TEARS IN THE SIDE OF THE TANK LED TO THE LEAKAGE. WE WERE UNAWARE THAT THE TRUCK BELONGED TO APC UNTIL SC STEP CONTACTED OUT OFFICE. FIRE CREWS RESPONDED OUT OF BELTON, ANDERSON COUNTY, AND DONALDSON CENTER. THE FIRE WAS PUT OUT BY USE OF FOAM. IT IS UNKNOWN HOW LING GASOLINE SPILLED OUT OF THE TANKER, HOWEVER CLEANUP EFFORTS REVEALED THAT A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT DID ACTUALLY SPILL THAT WAS UNBURNED. DUE TO THE LANDSCAPING AND CONTOUR, ALL OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN AN AREA OF APPROX. 5,000 FT. APC HIRED A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WHO IMMEDIATELY (AFTER THE FIRE WAS OUT ) VACUUMED UP THE STANDING PRODUCT/WATER THAT WAS VISIBLE ON THE GROUND. THE CLEANUP CREW EXCAVATED THE ENTIRE AREA OF THE RELEASE OVER THE NEXT SEVERAL DAYS, WITH THE EXCAVATION RANGING FROM 1 TO 16 FEET IN DEPTH. THE EXCAVATION WAS BACK-FILLED WITH FRESH FILL DIRT AND TOPSOIL, AND WAS SEEDED AND STRAWED TO COMPLETE THE EXCAVATION. ONGOING EFFORTS WILL INCLUDE A SINGLE  MONITORING WELL TO DETERMINE IF ANY EFFECT ON GROUNDWATER. EXPECTATIONS ARE THAT THE EAST MAJORITY OF THE CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS REMOVED, AND THE MONITORING PROCESS WILL BE SHORT.
column169: AFTER REVIEW BY SC HIGHWAY PATROL, SC START TRANSPORT POLICE AND FEDERAL MOTOR CARRIER SAFETY ADMINISTRATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER SIMPLY RAN OUT OF THE ROADWAY AND FAILED TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. APC HAS TRAINED EACH DRIVER ON THIS SPECIFIC ACCIDENT AND THE IMPORTANCE OF ALL DRIVERS TO MAINTAIN CONSTANT FOCUS ON THE TASK OF DRIVING. THERE ARE NOT FURTHER PREVENTIVE MEASURES THAT WILL BE TAKEN.
